<h2>Solar Panels in North Carolina</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>North Carolina ranks among the top states for solar energy potential, with excellent irradiance levels across all regions. The state receives between 4.2 to 5.2 peak sun hours daily, depending on location, with the coastal plains and Piedmont regions experiencing the highest levels. The western mountains still maintain good solar potential despite some topographical shading, typically receiving 4.0-4.5 peak sun hours daily. Seasonal variations show peak production during late spring and summer months, with May through August providing the highest energy yields.</p>

<p>A typical residential solar installation in North Carolina can produce between 1,200-1,400 kWh annually per kilowatt of installed capacity. This means a 6kW system, which is common for average-sized homes, can generate approximately 7,200-8,400 kWh per year. Given that the average North Carolina household consumes about 10,500 kWh annually, a properly sized solar system can offset 70-80% of typical electricity usage. The state's relatively stable weather patterns, with fewer severe storms than coastal areas further south, contribute to consistent solar production throughout the year.</p>

