<h2>North Carolina Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>North Carolina offers several valuable incentives for solar and HVAC installations, making energy improvements highly attractive for homeowners. The most significant benefit is the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit on the total cost of solar installations, including equipment, installation, and related system components. This credit applies to the full system cost and can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds current tax liability.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Tax Credit (30%):</strong> Available through 2032, this credit covers 30% of total solar installation costs including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and labor. The credit steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. Homeowners can apply this credit against federal income taxes owed, and unused portions can be rolled over to subsequent years.</li>
<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> North Carolina provides a property tax exemption for the added value of renewable energy equipment, meaning solar installations won't increase property tax assessments despite adding significant home value.</li>
<li><strong>Duke Energy Solar Rebates:</strong> Duke Energy offers various programs including net metering, allowing customers to sell excess solar production back to the grid at retail rates. The utility also provides energy efficiency rebates for qualifying HVAC equipment, including up to \$600 for heat pump installations and \$400 for high-efficiency air conditioning systems.</li>
<li><strong>Local Utility Programs:</strong> Many municipal utilities and electric cooperatives offer additional rebates and incentives. For example, some cooperatives provide low-interest loans for energy efficiency improvements and additional rebates for Energy Star certified equipment.</li>
<li><strong>Maximizing Incentives:</strong> To optimize benefits, homeowners should coordinate solar and HVAC installations to take advantage of multiple programs. Installing solar and upgrading HVAC systems simultaneously can provide compound savings through improved system efficiency and reduced overall energy consumption.</li>
</ul>

